    pageContent:
      "<p><br></p><p>Amid the U.S. election fervour and legal battles, democracy stands as a pivotal theme, igniting worldwide discussions on its future. President Biden champions democracy in his re-election campaign, starkly contrasted by Donald Trump's counterclaims. Central to the debate is the Trump v. Anderson case, probing the limits of democratic norms through the lens of ballot access in Colorado. This epitomizes the broader discourse on what democracy should embody, beyond the mere act of voting. Research highlights a worrying trend: many Americans equate democracy solely with voting, side-lining other vital participatory avenues like protests and civic engagement. Additionally, a prevalent belief conflates democracy with the American governance model, potentially stymieing democratic reforms and fostering disillusionment amidst political dissatisfaction. These narratives underscore the urgent need for a more nuanced understanding of democracy, challenging both Americans and the global community to rethink engagement and reform strategies. As the U.S. grapples with defining its democratic identity, the world watches, anticipating lessons that could reshape the global democratic landscape.</p>",
