    excerpt:
      "In the Dahra Global case, the Qatar Court of Appeal commuted the death sentences of eight former Indian Navy personnel, a decision that followed concerted efforts by India's External Affairs Ministry working in tandem with Qatari authorities and legal experts to safeguard the interests of the involved Indians. \n\nArrested in August 2022 on undisclosed charges of alleged espionage while employed by the private company Al Dahra, the details of the accusations and the recent appellate verdict remain confidential. However, the Indian Ministry of External Affairs' successful intervention to mitigate the sentences is a testament to the strong diplomatic ties between India and Qatar.\n\nQatar hosts over 700,000 Indian expatriates, constituting its largest expatriate community. These individuals contribute significantly across various sectors including medicine, engineering, education, finance, and more, earning respect for their hard work, integrity, and professional contributions to Qatar’s growth. \n\nThe sentence revision occurred nearly a month after Prime Minister Narendra Modi's dialogue with Sheikh Tamim bin Hamad Al Thani, the Emir (Ruler) of Qatar, during the COP28 summit in Dubai. Their discussions emphasised the bilateral partnership and the well-being of the Indian diaspora in Qatar, underscoring the mutual concern for citizen welfare. India and Qatar marked the silver jubilee of their diplomatic relations in 2023.\n\nIndia and Qatar have enjoyed a robust partnership characterised by steady growth in diverse sectors. This relationship is underpinned by historically close ties and regular, substantive engagement, including interactions at the highest governmental levels, reflecting a mutual commitment to further strengthening bilateral relations. The sentence reduction is a big win in itself for the Indian diplomacy and Indian officials are now working towards repatriating the prisoners from Qatar to India. ",

