      "<p><br></p><p>Recent observations have indicated a significant escalation of military activity by North Korea at the Demilitarized Zone (DMZ). South Korea has reported that the North has been deploying additional troops and military equipment to this highly sensitive area.</p><p><br></p><p>Key developments include the restoration of guard posts previously demolished under the 2018 inter-Korean military agreement. These actions are accompanied by the movement of antiaircraft guns to more forward positions within the DMZ. Additionally, the establishment of new recoilless rifle positions has been noted, marking a clear shift in North Korea's military posture.</p><p><br></p><p>This escalation can be traced back to 2020, when North Korea threatened to revoke certain aspects of inter-Korean agreements in response to anti-regime leaflets sent by defectors via balloons. The recent movements suggest that the Korean People's Army (KPA) may be initiating the implementation of this action plan, reversing previous demilitarization efforts and heightening tensions in the region.</p>",
